@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "About this Site";
}

<div class="container bg-body-tertiary rounded p-4 mb-4">
    <h2>@ViewData["Title"]</h2>
</div>

<div class="container">
    <h4>History</h4>
    <p>
        In June of 2016, the Pathfinder team, a subset of the ExpressRoute PM team, started building two
        physical customer repro labs at Equinix in Seattle, WA (SE3) and Ashburn, VA (DC2). Creating,
        maintaining, and removing individual tenant environments, ensuring they were isolated, secure,
        and usable was a labor and time intensive, manual effort.
    </p>
    <p>
        To ease the burden of multiple configurations (Juniper, Cisco, PowerShell, Hyper-V, etc) a
        spreadsheet was created. Called the "Configuration Generator" it was a macro-based (vba) Excel
        spreadsheet.
    </p>
    <p>
        The spreadsheet was used to generate the Azure PowerShell and on-premises network device config
        and VM config needed to run multiple concurrent customer environments, called "Tenants". This
        worked well for a few years, until a more robust conversation was needed between Azure and the
        configuration generator. Things like dynamic IP addresses, or ER Direct Port S-Tags which are
        generated in Azure when the environments are created, were needed in the on-premises configuration.
        Given these addresses and tags are dynamically assigned at creation, a multi-step back and forth
        was needed to utilize this information. To avoid building REST handlers in VBA in Excel, it was
        decided to move this tool to a web based application where interacting with online services can
        happen natively from the Configuration Generation tool.
    </p>
    <p>
        This site is the web evolution of that spreadsheet.
    </p>

    <h4>Site Construction</h4>

    <h5 class="mt-3">Platform &amp; Hosting</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Framework:</strong> ASP.NET Core (.NET 10) with C# 14, using Razor views and Bootstrap 5 styling with dark/light theme support.</li>
        <li><strong>Hosting:</strong> Azure App Service (Linux, West US 2) with Always On enabled to eliminate cold starts.</li>
        <li><strong>Database:</strong> Azure SQL Server (<code>labconfig.database.windows.net</code>) using Entity Framework Core 10 for data access.</li>
        <li><strong>Source Control:</strong> GitHub (<a href="https://github.com/tracsman/Projects" target="_blank">tracsman/Projects</a>) with GitHub Copilot-assisted development.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Authentication &amp; Authorization</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Authentication:</strong> Microsoft Entra ID via Easy Auth (App Service platform-level authentication). No passwords or connection string secrets are stored anywhere in the application.</li>
        <li><strong>SQL Authentication:</strong> System-assigned Managed Identity — the App Service identity is granted direct access to Azure SQL via Entra ID, eliminating the need for SQL credentials.</li>
        <li><strong>Local Development:</strong> Supports three auth modes — Easy Auth (App Service), code-based OIDC (with Entra ID app registration), or a fake development identity from <code>appsettings.Development.json</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Authorization:</strong> Custom role-based system using a <code>Users</code> table with per-user AuthLevels (0–15). Each controller action checks the user's AuthLevel to determine access to features like tenant management, admin functions, and user administration.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Data Model</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Tenants:</strong> Core entity representing a customer lab environment — includes ExpressRoute, VPN, VM, and addressing configuration for both Azure and on-premises resources.</li>
        <li><strong>Tenant Requests:</strong> Self-service lab request workflow — any authenticated user can submit a request, admins review and approve/reject from a queue.</li>
        <li><strong>Devices:</strong> Inventory of physical network devices (routers, switches) in each lab location.</li>
        <li><strong>IP Addresses:</strong> Public IP address management and assignment tracking.</li>
        <li><strong>Config:</strong> Generated configuration data for each tenant (network device configs, PowerShell scripts).</li>
        <li><strong>Regions:</strong> Lookup table of Azure regions available for tenant deployments.</li>
        <li><strong>Settings:</strong> Application-level configuration values stored in the database.</li>
        <li><strong>Users:</strong> User directory with Ninja (admin) flags, display names, and AuthLevel assignments.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Key Services</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>ConfigGenerator:</strong> The heart of the application — generates Juniper, Cisco, and PowerShell configuration scripts for each tenant based on their ExpressRoute, VPN, and VM settings. This is the web evolution of the original Excel/VBA "Configuration Generator" spreadsheet.</li>
        <li><strong>AuthLevelService:</strong> Resolves the authenticated user's email to their AuthLevel from the database on every request, injecting it into <code>HttpContext.Items</code> for use by controllers and views.</li>
        <li><strong>EasyAuthAuthenticationHandler:</strong> Custom authentication handler that reads Easy Auth platform headers (<code>X-MS-CLIENT-PRINCIPAL</code>) and constructs a <code>ClaimsPrincipal</code> with the user's name, email, and identity.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Lab Request Workflow</h5>
    <ol>
        <li>Any authenticated user submits a lab request via the <strong>Request a Lab</strong> form, specifying their ExpressRoute, VPN, VM, and region requirements.</li>
        <li>Admins (AuthLevel ≥ 8) see pending requests in the <strong>Admin → Tenant Requests</strong> queue, with a count badge on the nav menu.</li>
        <li>The reviewing admin selects a <strong>server preference</strong> (which determines the TenantID range and physical server assignment) and approves the request.</li>
        <li>On approval, a <strong>Tenant</strong> record is created in the database.</li>
        <li>A <strong>Power Automate</strong> flow monitors the database for approved requests and automatically creates/updates <strong>ADO Experiment work items</strong> in the <code>msazure/One</code> project using delegated Entra ID credentials.</li>
        <li>The admin is redirected to the <strong>Tenant Edit</strong> page to review and refine settings.</li>
    </ol>

    <h5>Deployment</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><strong><code>deploy-to-azure.ps1</code>:</strong> Full deployment script — creates the resource group, App Service Plan, Web App, enables Managed Identity, configures Easy Auth with Entra ID, sets up logging, builds, and deploys the application.</li>
        <li><strong><code>quick-deploy.ps1</code>:</strong> Fast redeployment — skips all infrastructure provisioning, just builds, packages, deploys, and warms up the app (including EF Core JIT compilation and Razor page pre-compilation).</li>
        <li><strong><code>Warmup.ps1</code>:</strong> Post-restart warmup — polls the <code>/warmup</code> endpoint to pre-compile EF Core and the DI pipeline, then touches all Razor pages to force JIT compilation.</li>
        <li><strong>Health endpoints:</strong> <code>/health</code> and <code>/warmup</code> are excluded from Easy Auth so deployment and monitoring tools can reach them without authentication.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>NuGet Packages</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><code>Azure.Identity</code> — <code>DefaultAzureCredential</code> for passwordless auth to Azure SQL</li>
        <li><code>Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore</code> + <code>SqlServer</code> — ORM and Azure SQL provider</li>
        <li><code>Microsoft.Identity.Web</code> — Entra ID / OIDC authentication for local development</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Roadmap</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Full tenant CRUD and configuration generation</li>
        <li>IP address management and assignment</li>
        <li>Workshop registration and management</li>
        <li>Automated Azure deployment orchestration</li>
        <li>On-prem automation of VM creation and network device configuration</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Known Issues</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>None, Jon don't write no bugs! (that make it into production)</li>
    </ul>
</div>

